1
00:00:50,075 --> 00:00:53,784
<i>Let us praise famous men...</i>

2
00:00:54,675 --> 00:00:56,666
<i>... and our fathers that begat us.</i>

3
00:00:58,555 --> 00:01:00,511
<i>All these men...</i>

4
00:01:00,595 --> 00:01:02,745
<i>... were honoured in their generations...</i>

5
00:01:02,835 --> 00:01:06,589
<i>... and were a glory in their days.</i>

6
00:01:06,675 --> 00:01:10,463
We are here today to give thanks...

7
00:01:10,555 --> 00:01:13,752
...for the life of Harold Abrahams.

8
00:01:15,315 --> 00:01:18,148
To honour the legend.

9
00:01:19,195 --> 00:01:21,663
Now there are just two of us -

10
00:01:21,755 --> 00:01:24,144
young Aubrey Montague...

11
00:01:24,235 --> 00:01:26,385
...and myself -

12
00:01:26,475 --> 00:01:28,864
who can close our eyes...

13
00:01:28,955 --> 00:01:32,868
...and remember those few young men...

14
00:01:32,955 --> 00:01:35,344
...with hope in our hearts...

15
00:01:35,435 --> 00:01:38,871
<i>... and wings on our heels.</i>

16
00:04:10,115 --> 00:04:13,073
<i> Cariton Hotel, Broadstairs, Kent.</i>

17
00:04:13,155 --> 00:04:15,146
<i>28th June, 1924.</i>

18
00:04:15,355 --> 00:04:19,746
<i>Dear Mum. I'm most awfully sorry about</i>
<i>your cold and the general dreariness.</i>

19
00:04:19,835 --> 00:04:22,303
<i>We're also having</i>
<i>quite bad weather here, too.</i>

20
00:04:22,395 --> 00:04:25,751
<i>Thanks for your letters.</i>
<i>I'm sorry you and Pa are disappointed...</i>

21
00:04:25,835 --> 00:04:29,510
<i>... I should be letting the Olympic Games</i>
<i>interfere with my shorthand.</i>

22
00:04:29,595 --> 00:04:33,793
<i>But if you were my age, with a chance</i>
<i>to win the Worid Championship in Paris...</i>

23
00:04:33,875 --> 00:04:36,150
<i>... you would be just as big a fool as I am.</i>

24
00:04:36,235 --> 00:04:40,592
<i>By the way, it's awfully kind of Pa</i>
<i>to finance me here, in spite of my idiocy.</i>

25
00:04:40,675 --> 00:04:44,668
<i>It's marvellous for esprit de corps.</i>
<i>Most of the chaps have managed to get down.</i>

26
00:04:44,755 --> 00:04:47,633
- Cricket, Montague, in the ballroom.
- Now!

27
00:04:49,075 --> 00:04:50,906
No ball!

28
00:04:50,995 --> 00:04:52,986
Come on, Aubrey, the old leg break.

29
00:05:03,515 --> 00:05:06,473
- Howzat!
- Not out.

30
00:05:06,555 --> 00:05:08,944
What? You could hear it
in bloody Bournemouth!

31
00:05:09,035 --> 00:05:11,595
- Come on, Liddell, my innings.
- I didn't touch it.

32
00:05:11,675 --> 00:05:15,224
- You heard the crack of my wrist.
- I saw the bloody thing bend! Andy!

33
00:05:15,315 --> 00:05:17,226
No tickle for me.

34
00:05:17,315 --> 00:05:20,273
He's out, I tell you.
You're all deaf and bloody blind.

35
00:05:20,355 --> 00:05:22,949
Aubrey, I ask you, for God's sake!

36
00:05:26,835 --> 00:05:28,826
It's not fair!

37
00:05:34,115 --> 00:05:35,912
All right.

38
00:05:39,115 --> 00:05:41,504
<i> Harold's here. As intense as ever.</i>

39
00:05:41,595 --> 00:05:44,553
<i>Just as he was</i>
<i>on our very first day at Cambridge.</i>

40
00:05:44,635 --> 00:05:46,626
<i>I remember we shared a taxi together.</i>

41
00:06:12,635 --> 00:06:14,626
I'll take these.

42
00:06:18,315 --> 00:06:20,385
- See you inside, Aubrey.
- Right.

43
00:06:22,235 --> 00:06:24,385
Thank you.

44
00:06:28,675 --> 00:06:30,666
- Name, please.
- We're new.

45
00:06:30,755 --> 00:06:32,871
I can see that, laddie. What's your name?

46
00:06:32,955 --> 00:06:34,946
Abrahams. HM.

47
00:06:35,555 --> 00:06:39,070
- Top of the list. Repton. That the one?
- That's it. Left a year ago.

48
00:06:39,155 --> 00:06:42,625
- Been doing your bit, 'ave you? France?
- No. Joined too late.

49
00:06:42,715 --> 00:06:44,307
Bad luck, lad.

50
00:06:44,395 --> 00:06:46,863
Many a dead man
would have liked a share of it.

51
00:06:46,955 --> 00:06:48,946
You're right there, son.

52
00:06:49,795 --> 00:06:52,025
Welcome to Caius.

53
00:06:52,915 --> 00:06:56,430
- Sign here.
- Thank you.

54
00:06:56,515 --> 00:07:00,394
It's across the courtyard,
top right-hand corner, up the stairs.

55
00:07:00,475 --> 00:07:01,874
Thanks.

56
00:07:01,955 --> 00:07:03,513
By the way, what are your names?

57
00:07:03,595 --> 00:07:06,905
Rogers, head porter,
and this is Mr Ratcliffe, my assistant.

58
00:07:06,995 --> 00:07:08,986
Well, Mr Rogers, Ratcliffe...

59
00:07:09,075 --> 00:07:12,306
...I ceased to be a "laddie" when
I took up the King's commissión.

60
00:07:12,395 --> 00:07:15,546
- Is that clear?
- Yes... Mr Abrahams.

61
00:07:15,635 --> 00:07:17,546
- Quite clear.
- Thank you.

62
00:07:17,635 --> 00:07:20,024
I'd be obliged if you'd remember it.

63
00:07:20,115 --> 00:07:22,106
- See you later.
- Fine.

64
00:07:23,755 --> 00:07:26,349
What's your friend studying, then, son?

65
00:07:26,435 --> 00:07:28,426
Barrack-room law?

66
00:07:28,955 --> 00:07:30,946
- I've no idea.
- Mm.

67
00:07:31,035 --> 00:07:32,673
One thing's certain.

68
00:07:32,755 --> 00:07:37,306
A name like Abrahams, he won't be
in the chapel choir, now, will he?

69
00:07:37,395 --> 00:07:39,511
- Name?
- Montague.

70
00:07:39,595 --> 00:07:41,586
- What?
- Montague.

71
00:08:28,715 --> 00:08:30,751
I take the war list...

72
00:08:30,835 --> 00:08:32,826
...and I run down it.

73
00:08:34,235 --> 00:08:36,749
Name after name which I cannot read...

74
00:08:36,835 --> 00:08:40,066
...and which we, who are older than you...

75
00:08:40,155 --> 00:08:42,749
...cannot hear, without emotion.

76
00:08:44,235 --> 00:08:47,068
Names which will be only names to you...

77
00:08:47,155 --> 00:08:49,146
...the new college.

78
00:08:49,235 --> 00:08:53,911
But which to us summon up face after face...

79
00:08:55,235 --> 00:08:59,023
...full of honesty and goodness...

80
00:08:59,115 --> 00:09:00,912
...zeal and vigour...

81
00:09:00,995 --> 00:09:03,668
...and intellectual promise.

82
00:09:05,195 --> 00:09:07,311
The flower of a generation.

83
00:09:07,395 --> 00:09:09,351
The glory of England...

84
00:09:09,435 --> 00:09:11,426
...and they died for England...

85
00:09:11,515 --> 00:09:13,745
...and all that England stands for.

86
00:09:14,835 --> 00:09:18,987
And now by tragic necessity,
their dreams have become yours.

87
00:09:19,755 --> 00:09:22,827
Let me exhort you. Examine yourselves.

88
00:09:22,915 --> 00:09:24,906
Let each of you discover...

89
00:09:24,995 --> 00:09:28,032
...where your true chance of greatness lies.

90
00:09:28,755 --> 00:09:30,746
For their sakes...

91
00:09:30,835 --> 00:09:35,113
...for the sake of your college
and your country, seize this chance.

92
00:09:35,195 --> 00:09:37,186
Rejoice in it...

93
00:09:37,275 --> 00:09:41,553
...and let no power or persuasión
deter you in your task.

94
00:09:44,675 --> 00:09:47,508
<i> Thursday, October 10th, 1919.</i>

95
00:09:47,595 --> 00:09:49,950
<i>My first day at Cambridge was rounded off...</i>

96
00:09:50,035 --> 00:09:52,754
<i>... by the freshmen's dinner,</i>
<i>a sumptuous affair.</i>

97
00:09:52,835 --> 00:09:54,985
<i>The master gave us a moving speech...</i>

98
00:09:55,075 --> 00:09:58,590
<i>... and I'm now eagerly awaiting</i>
<i>the start of term proper.</i>

99
00:09:58,955 --> 00:10:01,594
Rugby club, golfing society, tennis...

100
00:10:01,675 --> 00:10:04,553
...squash club, flora and fauna, philately.

101
00:10:04,635 --> 00:10:06,626
Is that all? You're an idle man!

102
00:10:06,715 --> 00:10:10,469
- I've got to work some time.
- Try bird-watching. You can take a book.

103
00:10:10,555 --> 00:10:12,546
How can I watch if I'm reading a book?

104
00:10:12,635 --> 00:10:15,388
Follow in the footsteps of WG.
Any Yorkshiremen here?

105
00:10:15,475 --> 00:10:17,386
I can't bat for toffee.

106
00:10:19,275 --> 00:10:21,072
# Upon the battle scene

107
00:10:21,155 --> 00:10:22,793
# They fight the foe together

108
00:10:22,875 --> 00:10:24,672
# There every mother's son

109
00:10:24,755 --> 00:10:26,871
# Prepared to fight or fall is

110
00:10:26,955 --> 00:10:30,345
# The enemy of one the enemy of all is

111
00:10:30,835 --> 00:10:34,544
# The enemy of one the enemy of all is

112
00:10:35,395 --> 00:10:37,545
- Abrahams, HM.
- Can you manage a tenor?

113
00:10:37,635 --> 00:10:40,866
- We're desperately short of tenors.
- Only under torture.

114
00:10:40,955 --> 00:10:43,753
- Aubrey. Sing, do you?
- School choir, that's all.

115
00:10:43,835 --> 00:10:45,234
You, Stallard?

116
00:10:45,315 --> 00:10:47,670
They kicked me out of <i>Ring-a-ring o'Roses.</i>

117
00:10:47,755 --> 00:10:49,905
Sorry about that. We can't all be gifted.

118
00:10:49,995 --> 00:10:52,225
# If everybody's somebody

119
00:10:52,315 --> 00:10:54,465
# Then no one's anybody

120
00:10:54,555 --> 00:10:56,910
- Put my friend here down as well.
- Steady on.

121
00:10:56,995 --> 00:10:59,714
Splendid! Rehearsals start on Monday.
<i>Iolanthe.</i>

122
00:10:59,795 --> 00:11:03,868
- I was a boy alto.
- Perfect! You can be Queen of the Fairies.

123
00:11:03,955 --> 00:11:06,264
Where were you
when your country needed you?

124
00:11:06,355 --> 00:11:10,633
We have a duty, a solemn duty, to those
millions of lives needlessly slaughtered!

125
00:11:10,715 --> 00:11:13,434
# When the boys are far away

126
00:11:13,515 --> 00:11:17,986
# They dream of home

127
00:11:19,115 --> 00:11:21,106
Well, glad to have you, Stallard.

128
00:11:21,195 --> 00:11:23,584
Good middle-distance men
don't grow on trees.

129
00:11:23,675 --> 00:11:25,666
I can't vouch for those times.

130
00:11:26,995 --> 00:11:29,907
Taken with the school alarm clock,
most of them.

131
00:11:29,995 --> 00:11:33,146
Give or take a second,
they're good enough for me.

132
00:11:33,955 --> 00:11:37,152
Have you come across a fellow
called Abrahams? HM Abrahams?

133
00:11:37,235 --> 00:11:39,226
He's challenged for the college dash.

134
00:11:39,355 --> 00:11:41,346
What's so special about that?

135
00:11:41,435 --> 00:11:44,108
In all the 700 years, nobody's ever done it.

136
00:11:44,195 --> 00:11:45,674
Right, what do you do?

137
00:12:02,195 --> 00:12:04,425
Right, chaps, thank you! Thank you.

138
00:12:05,555 --> 00:12:08,513
Let it be known that HM Abrahams
of Gonville and Caius...

139
00:12:08,595 --> 00:12:11,473
...has formally made challenge
for the college dash.

140
00:12:12,875 --> 00:12:14,513
You show 'em, Harold!

141
00:12:14,595 --> 00:12:16,870
For those not familiar with the rules...

142
00:12:16,955 --> 00:12:20,504
The challenger will attempt
to run around the court perimeter...

143
00:12:20,595 --> 00:12:22,790
...to and from a point beneath the clock...

144
00:12:22,875 --> 00:12:25,753
...within the time taken
by the clock to strike midday.

145
00:12:25,835 --> 00:12:29,544
A distance traditionally
recognised as one of 188 paces.

146
00:12:29,635 --> 00:12:32,945
I say, Abrahams, what have you got
on your feet? Rockets?

147
00:12:33,035 --> 00:12:35,310
The challenge will commence on the...

148
00:12:35,395 --> 00:12:38,944
- Abrahams, you haven't got a chance!
- Do it for Israel!

149
00:12:39,035 --> 00:12:41,344
The challenge commences
on the stroke of one.

150
00:12:41,435 --> 00:12:44,313
The challenger must finish
before the stroke of 12.

151
00:12:44,395 --> 00:12:46,386
Come on, Abrahams, you swank!

152
00:12:46,475 --> 00:12:48,830
Will the challenger make himself ready?

153
00:12:48,915 --> 00:12:51,713
Whoa!

154
00:12:56,275 --> 00:12:59,153
This Abrahams.
What do you know about him?

155
00:12:59,235 --> 00:13:01,146
Repton chap.

156
00:13:01,235 --> 00:13:02,463
Jewish.

157
00:13:02,555 --> 00:13:05,786
- His father's a financier in the city.
- Financier?

158
00:13:05,875 --> 00:13:08,309
What's that supposed to mean, I wonder?

159
00:13:08,395 --> 00:13:10,386
I imagine he lends money.

160
00:13:11,075 --> 00:13:13,066
Exactly.

161
00:13:13,155 --> 00:13:15,305
And what do they say about the son?

162
00:13:15,395 --> 00:13:18,228
Academically sound. Arrogant.

163
00:13:18,315 --> 00:13:20,226
Defensive to the point of pugnacity.

164
00:13:20,315 --> 00:13:22,783
Mm. As they invariably are.

165
00:13:23,395 --> 00:13:26,228
Yet possessing
a keen sense of duty and loyalty.

166
00:13:29,595 --> 00:13:31,984
Do they say he can run?

167
00:13:32,075 --> 00:13:33,827
Like the wind.

168
00:13:37,755 --> 00:13:41,225
Gentlemen, would you draw back, please?
Away from the course.

169
00:13:41,315 --> 00:13:42,907
Thank you.

170
00:13:42,995 --> 00:13:44,986
Mr Abrahams, your position, please.

171
00:13:45,755 --> 00:13:48,315
Owing to the absence
of any other challenger...

172
00:13:48,435 --> 00:13:50,232
...Mr Abrahams will run alone.

173
00:13:50,315 --> 00:13:52,306
Not so, Mr Starter!

174
00:13:55,955 --> 00:13:58,150
Your name and college, if you please, sir.

175
00:13:58,235 --> 00:14:01,033
Lindsay. I race beside my friend here.

176
00:14:01,115 --> 00:14:04,630
We challenge in the name
of Repton, Eton and Caius.

177
00:14:07,755 --> 00:14:10,110
<i>- </i> I didn't know you ran.
- Nor I you.

178
00:14:10,195 --> 00:14:13,824
Some chap just told me about this.
I thought I'd come and push you along.

179
00:14:13,915 --> 00:14:15,394
- Delighted.
- Splendid.

180
00:14:15,475 --> 00:14:16,544
Good luck.

181
00:14:16,635 --> 00:14:19,433
Gentlemen, to your marks, if you please.

182
00:14:21,475 --> 00:14:24,228
Now remember, on the first strike of 12.

183
00:14:48,395 --> 00:14:50,386
Come on!

184
00:15:08,155 --> 00:15:09,952
Eight!

185
00:15:11,075 --> 00:15:13,066
Nine!

186
00:15:14,515 --> 00:15:16,506
Ten!

187
00:15:17,435 --> 00:15:18,948
- Eleven!
- Go on! Go on!

188
00:15:34,875 --> 00:15:36,672
Did they both do it?

189
00:15:36,755 --> 00:15:38,746
I think not.

190
00:15:38,835 --> 00:15:42,145
- Young Lindsay failed by a whisker.
- Pity.

191
00:15:42,235 --> 00:15:46,148
<i> Well, it's been done.</i>
<i>And by a Caius man! You must be very proud.</i>

192
00:15:46,235 --> 00:15:48,226
<i>The first man in seven centuries.</i>

193
00:15:48,315 --> 00:15:53,309
<i>Perhaps they really are</i>
<i>God's chosen people, after all.</i>

194
00:15:54,955 --> 00:15:57,515
<i>I doubt if there's a swifter man</i>
<i>in the kingdom.</i>

195
00:15:59,915 --> 00:16:01,906
Get to your marks.

196
00:16:06,035 --> 00:16:08,230
Get set.

197
00:16:43,755 --> 00:16:47,794
<i> He may be your best friend, Sandy,</i>
<i>but he's my best brother.</i>

198
00:16:47,875 --> 00:16:51,026
<i>I'm thinking of him</i>
<i>and not your blessed athletics team.</i>

199
00:16:51,115 --> 00:16:54,027
<i>His heart's set on following Father</i>
<i>in the missión.</i>

200
00:16:54,115 --> 00:16:57,107
Do you not think he's busy enough
without taking up racing?

201
00:16:57,195 --> 00:17:00,232
He's fast, Jennie.
You've seen him with a ball in his hands.

202
00:17:00,315 --> 00:17:02,351
I've seen him with a Bible in his hands.

203
00:17:02,435 --> 00:17:04,426
And I know which is the most important.

204
00:17:04,515 --> 00:17:06,506
You can't deny him the chance.

205
00:17:06,595 --> 00:17:09,155
Get him on the track, I'm telling you...

206
00:17:09,235 --> 00:17:11,829
Don't tell me, Sandy. I don't want to hear.

207
00:17:11,915 --> 00:17:13,871
Eric's special to me. Precious.

208
00:17:13,955 --> 00:17:17,550
I don't want his work spoilt
with all this running talk, do you hear?

209
00:17:26,035 --> 00:17:29,027
There you are. Well done.

210
00:17:36,755 --> 00:17:38,825
You know, ladies and gentlemen...

211
00:17:38,915 --> 00:17:42,430
...one of the compensations
of achieving a certain notoriety...

212
00:17:42,515 --> 00:17:44,153
...if only as a rugby player...

213
00:17:44,235 --> 00:17:47,272
...is that occasionally
you're asked to give things away.

214
00:17:49,155 --> 00:17:51,544
It's often said that giving beats receiving.

215
00:17:51,635 --> 00:17:53,466
Let me tell you -

216
00:17:53,555 --> 00:17:56,149
the look of delight
on those little boys' faces...

217
00:17:56,235 --> 00:18:00,547
...was worth ten of the tin pots gathering
dust on my Edinburgh sideboard.

218
00:18:02,275 --> 00:18:04,470
When we were in China, my father here...

219
00:18:04,555 --> 00:18:08,343
...was always waxing lyrical
about his wee home in the glen.

220
00:18:09,155 --> 00:18:11,510
But being oriental-born myself...

221
00:18:11,595 --> 00:18:14,155
...like my brothers and my sister here...

222
00:18:14,235 --> 00:18:16,829
...I suffered from a natural incredulity.

223
00:18:17,915 --> 00:18:19,906
But looking about me now -

224
00:18:19,995 --> 00:18:21,986
the heather on the hills -

225
00:18:23,235 --> 00:18:25,465
I can see he was right.

226
00:18:25,555 --> 00:18:27,546
It's very special.

227
00:18:31,715 --> 00:18:33,626
Thank you for welcoming us home.

228
00:18:33,715 --> 00:18:35,194
And thank you...

229
00:18:35,275 --> 00:18:38,551
...for reminding me that I am,
and will be whilst I breathe...

230
00:18:40,395 --> 00:18:42,670
...a Scot.

231
00:18:46,395 --> 00:18:48,545
Mr Provost, sir.

232
00:18:48,635 --> 00:18:51,354
Before you allow Eric here to go...

233
00:18:51,755 --> 00:18:55,634
Is it not true that the main event
of the meeting is still to be run?

234
00:18:55,715 --> 00:18:57,353
It is. Aye.

235
00:18:57,435 --> 00:18:59,551
The 200-yards open championship.

236
00:18:59,635 --> 00:19:03,025
It's the last event
of this gathering, by tradition.

237
00:19:03,115 --> 00:19:06,312
Do you not think,
if we can find him some kit...

238
00:19:06,395 --> 00:19:10,149
...we might persuade Scotland's
finest wing to show us his paces?

239
00:19:13,155 --> 00:19:15,146
What do you say, Eric?

240
00:19:25,155 --> 00:19:27,385
To your marks!

241
00:19:27,475 --> 00:19:28,794
Get set!

242
00:20:36,235 --> 00:20:38,624
Didn't I tell you, Eric? Didn't I tell you?

243
00:20:43,515 --> 00:20:46,393
Surely a touch of liberality
would do no harm.

244
00:20:46,475 --> 00:20:49,831
Sandy, the kingdom of God
is not a democracy.

245
00:20:49,915 --> 00:20:52,383
The Lord never seeks re-election.

246
00:20:52,475 --> 00:20:55,035
There's no discussión, no deliberation...

247
00:20:55,115 --> 00:20:57,549
...no referenda as to which road to take.

248
00:20:58,355 --> 00:21:00,471
There's one right, one wrong...

249
00:21:00,555 --> 00:21:02,546
...one absolute ruler.

250
00:21:02,635 --> 00:21:07,072
- A dictator, you mean.
- Aye, but a benign, loving dictator.

251
00:21:07,155 --> 00:21:09,669
So much for your freedom of choice.

252
00:21:09,755 --> 00:21:11,825
You've still got a choice, Sandy.

253
00:21:12,715 --> 00:21:14,865
Nobody's forcing you to follow it.

254
00:21:19,515 --> 00:21:21,710
Ooh! Hey, hey!

255
00:21:22,835 --> 00:21:24,905
- Do you know what day it is?
- Yeah.

256
00:21:24,995 --> 00:21:26,986
- Tell me, then.
- Sunday.

257
00:21:27,075 --> 00:21:29,589
The Sabbath's not a day
for playing football, is it?

258
00:21:29,675 --> 00:21:31,154
No.

259
00:21:31,235 --> 00:21:34,386
- Are you up early in the morning?
- Me ma gets me up at seven.

260
00:21:34,475 --> 00:21:36,466
We'll have a game then, then. OK?

261
00:21:36,555 --> 00:21:38,546
Mr Liddell, is it OK if me da comes?

262
00:21:38,635 --> 00:21:40,751
Sure. Bring your whole family.

263
00:21:40,835 --> 00:21:42,826
I'll give ye a five-goal start.

264
00:21:42,915 --> 00:21:45,190
You've got a train to catch at nine.

265
00:21:45,275 --> 00:21:47,266
There's plenty of time.

266
00:21:47,355 --> 00:21:50,711
Do you want the kid to grow up
thinking God's a spoilsport?

267
00:21:54,355 --> 00:21:56,869
If I may, I'd like to propose a toast.

268
00:21:56,955 --> 00:21:58,593
To the Liddell family...

269
00:21:58,675 --> 00:22:01,143
...whom I'm fortunate enough
to call my friends.

270
00:22:01,235 --> 00:22:03,988
The Reverend JD, Mrs L, young Ernest.

271
00:22:04,835 --> 00:22:07,793
<i>Bon voyage</i> and safe journey back to China.

272
00:22:07,875 --> 00:22:10,150
May the years ahead be happy and content.

273
00:22:10,235 --> 00:22:13,466
For those who remain,
may God protect them...

274
00:22:13,555 --> 00:22:15,227
...inspire them...

275
00:22:15,315 --> 00:22:17,067
...and lead them to glory.

276
00:22:17,155 --> 00:22:19,225
Thank you, Sandy. That was very nice.

277
00:22:19,315 --> 00:22:21,988
I'm relying on you now
to keep them all out of mischief.

278
00:22:22,075 --> 00:22:26,307
That I will, Mrs L. If they do transgress,
I'll pop the details on a postcard.

279
00:22:26,395 --> 00:22:29,353
You can read all about it
before you can say Marco Polo.

280
00:22:29,435 --> 00:22:31,471
Cost you a fortune in postage stamps.

281
00:22:31,555 --> 00:22:33,830
Don't worry. I shall protect my investment.

282
00:22:33,915 --> 00:22:36,873
I'm going to rule you with a rod of iron.

283
00:22:38,475 --> 00:22:40,750
We're going to have to watch ourselves!

284
00:22:44,315 --> 00:22:46,385
You're a very lucky young man, Eric.

285
00:22:46,475 --> 00:22:48,670
You're the proud possessor of many gifts.

286
00:22:48,755 --> 00:22:51,553
And it's your sacred duty
to put them to good use.

287
00:22:51,635 --> 00:22:54,991
Dad's right. Run like we know you can,
strong and true.

288
00:22:55,075 --> 00:22:57,828
The missión cannot but gain
by your success.

289
00:22:58,835 --> 00:23:01,349
What we need now is a muscular Christian.

290
00:23:01,835 --> 00:23:04,588
To make folks sit up and notice.

291
00:23:04,675 --> 00:23:07,030
How good are you, Eric?

292
00:23:07,755 --> 00:23:11,145
Sandy reckons he'll run for Scotland
before the month's out.

293
00:23:11,235 --> 00:23:13,669
Then after that... the sky's the limit.

294
00:23:13,755 --> 00:23:15,188
Meaning what?

295
00:23:16,155 --> 00:23:18,146
The Olympic Games, maybe?

296
00:23:19,835 --> 00:23:23,145
Eric, you can praise the Lord
by peeling a spud...

297
00:23:23,235 --> 00:23:25,226
...if you peel it to perfection.

298
00:23:25,315 --> 00:23:28,466
Don't compromise.
Compromise is a language of the devil.

299
00:23:28,555 --> 00:23:30,511
Run in God's name...

300
00:23:30,595 --> 00:23:33,109
