4-1 Liddell! What are you asking?

405
00:31:50,515 --> 00:31:52,506
£25, Liddell to win.

406
00:32:04,915 --> 00:32:06,906
Mr Mussabini, I believe.

407
00:32:06,995 --> 00:32:10,067
My name's Keddie. Colonel John Keddie.

408
00:32:10,155 --> 00:32:12,430
- I'm...
- President of the Scottish Three A's.

409
00:32:12,515 --> 00:32:15,188
I know, and I'm glad to know you, sir.

410
00:32:15,275 --> 00:32:17,948
- <i>Ah, monsieur Sam! Bonjour.</i>
- <i>Ah, bonjour.</i>

411
00:32:18,075 --> 00:32:19,633
- How's the leg?
- OK.

412
00:32:19,715 --> 00:32:21,307
Nasty fall you took.

413
00:32:21,435 --> 00:32:23,426
<i>Enchanté.</i> Good luck.

414
00:32:23,555 --> 00:32:25,625
You're very welcome here, of course.

415
00:32:25,715 --> 00:32:28,673
But we do have a strict amateur code.

416
00:32:29,475 --> 00:32:31,466
Colonel, don't worry your head.

417
00:32:31,555 --> 00:32:33,386
I'm here spectating, that's all.

418
00:32:33,475 --> 00:32:35,750
Ah, good. I felt sure you would understand.

419
00:32:36,835 --> 00:32:38,826
Well, to battle!

420
00:32:38,915 --> 00:32:40,906
I hope you enjoy the games.

421
00:32:41,755 --> 00:32:43,746
Games? You must be joking.

422
00:32:43,835 --> 00:32:46,224
I've seen better-organised riots.

423
00:32:46,315 --> 00:32:49,148
Come on, Scotland!

424
00:32:49,235 --> 00:32:51,226
<i>Vive la France!</i>

425
00:32:59,835 --> 00:33:01,826
Gentlemen, get to your marks.

426
00:33:08,155 --> 00:33:09,668
Get set.

427
00:33:20,995 --> 00:33:22,986
Get up, lad. Get up.

428
00:33:27,755 --> 00:33:29,825
Yeah.

429
00:33:33,755 --> 00:33:35,632
He'll never do it.

430
00:33:35,715 --> 00:33:38,070
Don't you believe it. His head's not back yet.

431
00:33:47,475 --> 00:33:49,466
Come on, Eric!

432
00:34:21,955 --> 00:34:23,946
Get back! Give him air!

433
00:34:26,235 --> 00:34:28,624
Well done, Eric, son. Well done.

434
00:34:28,715 --> 00:34:31,673
He'll be right in ajiffy.
I'll go away and get his clothes.

435
00:34:36,835 --> 00:34:40,225
You take good care
of this lad o' yours, Mr McGrath.

436
00:34:40,315 --> 00:34:44,194
Because if you drop him,
you'll never find another one like this.

437
00:34:44,275 --> 00:34:47,312
It's not the prettiest quarter
I've ever seen, Mr Liddell.

438
00:34:47,395 --> 00:34:49,386
But certainly the bravest.

439
00:34:49,475 --> 00:34:51,466
Get him up. Come on, gently.

440
00:34:56,755 --> 00:34:58,746
Keep your arm around.

441
00:35:19,355 --> 00:35:21,346
Mr Mussabini.

442
00:35:23,395 --> 00:35:25,386
Mr Abrahams, is it?

443
00:35:26,075 --> 00:35:28,464
So you've travelled 300 mile just to see me?

444
00:35:28,555 --> 00:35:30,147
You and Liddell.

445
00:35:30,235 --> 00:35:32,226
I'd heard you were both the best.

446
00:35:32,315 --> 00:35:34,306
And what do you think now?

447
00:35:34,395 --> 00:35:36,386
Eric Liddell?

448
00:35:36,475 --> 00:35:39,990
I've never seen such drive,
such commitment in a runner.

449
00:35:40,555 --> 00:35:42,546
He runs like a wild animal.

450
00:35:42,635 --> 00:35:44,353
He unnerves me.

451
00:35:44,435 --> 00:35:46,153
So he should.

452
00:35:46,235 --> 00:35:48,749
He frightens the living daylights out of me.

453
00:35:48,835 --> 00:35:51,474
I want you to help me take him on.

454
00:35:53,995 --> 00:35:56,065
Tell me, Mr Abrahams. Are you married?

455
00:35:56,155 --> 00:35:58,146
No. Why?

456
00:35:58,235 --> 00:35:59,634
Well...

457
00:35:59,715 --> 00:36:02,388
...when the right girl comes along...

458
00:36:02,475 --> 00:36:05,626
...how will you feel if she pops the question?

459
00:36:08,195 --> 00:36:10,186
You see, Mr Abrahams...

460
00:36:10,275 --> 00:36:12,152
...like the bridegroom...

461
00:36:12,235 --> 00:36:14,624
...it's the coach that should do the asking.

462
00:36:15,755 --> 00:36:17,711
Mr Mussabini...

463
00:36:17,795 --> 00:36:19,751
...I can run fast.

464
00:36:19,835 --> 00:36:22,588
With your help, I think I can run even faster.

465
00:36:22,675 --> 00:36:24,905
Perhaps faster than any man ever ran.

466
00:36:25,635 --> 00:36:27,626
I want that Olympic medal.

467
00:36:28,435 --> 00:36:30,426
Now, I can see it there.

468
00:36:30,515 --> 00:36:32,631
It's waiting for me.

469
00:36:32,715 --> 00:36:34,706
But I can't get it on my own.

470
00:36:40,955 --> 00:36:43,469
Well, we've an old saying in my game, son.

471
00:36:44,395 --> 00:36:46,511
You can't put in what God's left out.

472
00:36:47,355 --> 00:36:49,232
Now, you leave it to me.

473
00:36:49,315 --> 00:36:52,546
I'll watch you. I'll observe.
And if I think I can help -

474
00:36:53,715 --> 00:36:56,275
if I can see the big prize hanging there -

475
00:36:56,355 --> 00:36:58,744
believe me, I won't waste any time.

476
00:36:58,835 --> 00:37:01,110
When we meet again...

477
00:37:01,195 --> 00:37:03,186
...l'll be the one that does the begging.

478
00:37:03,275 --> 00:37:05,152
So you will watch me?

479
00:37:05,235 --> 00:37:07,226
Son, if you're good enough...

480
00:37:08,715 --> 00:37:11,434
...l'll take you apart piece by bloody piece.

481
00:37:12,075 --> 00:37:14,066
Thank you.

